<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_01.jpg" alt="Robert Taylor next to one of the EPA air monitoring sites in LaPlace, Louisiana. (All Photos: Julie Dermansky)" width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Robert Taylor next to one of the EPA air monitoring sites in LaPlace, Louisiana. (All Photos: Julie Dermansky)" width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_01.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Robert Taylor next to one of the EPA air monitoring sites in LaPlace, Louisiana. (All Photos: Julie Dermansky)</span></span></p>
<div class="well well-small"><a href="https://truthout.org/support-us/#top" style=" line-height: 1.4em;">Support from readers keeps Truthout 100 percent independent. If you like what you&rsquo;re reading, make a donation! </a></div>
<p>This past year in Louisiana&rsquo;s St. John the Baptist Parish, a small group of residents began organizing their community to compel the state to protect them against an invisible menace: the air they breathe. Their parish, the Louisiana equivalent of a county, is situated in what&rsquo;s known as Cancer Alley, an industrial corridor between Baton Rouge and New Orleans that hosts more than 100 petrochemical factories.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.desmogblog.com/2017/04/19/st-john-baptist-parish-fight-clean-air-louisiana-cancer-alley-denka-chloroprene" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.desmogblog.com/2017/04/19/st-john-baptist-parish-fight-clean-air-louisiana-cancer-alley-denka-chloroprene&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1515613069646000&amp;usg=AFQjCNE4EzXTZr3D_OWLKX6BjehuzgpFfA" data-external="true">At the helm of the battle</a> is the Concerned Citizens of St. John, a diverse group of parish residents pushing back against the area&rsquo;s historically bad &mdash; and worsening &mdash; industrial pollution. &ldquo;One thing we all have in common is a desire for clean air,&rdquo; the group&rsquo;s founder, Robert Taylor, told me. Over the next year, the burgeoning group plans to get political and broaden its reach by banding together with similar groups in the region.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255395">
<h2>Uncompromised, uncompromising news</h2>
<p>Get reliable, independent news and commentary delivered to your inbox every day.</p>
