<p>Taylor, a 76-year-old retired general contractor, recently spoke to me about the group from California, where he spent Christmas with his wife, who is recuperating from a stroke. Their extended family insisted Taylor keep his wife away from the Louisiana parish&rsquo;s polluted air.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_02.jpg" alt="Robert Taylor at a Concerned Citizens of St. John meeting at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve, Louisiana, on June 27." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Robert Taylor at a Concerned Citizens of St. John meeting at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve, Louisiana, on June 27." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_02.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Robert Taylor at a Concerned Citizens of St. John meeting at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve, Louisiana, on June 27.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_03.jpg" alt="Lydia Gerard, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, holding up a new sign at their public meeting on August 15." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Lydia Gerard, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, holding up a new sign at their public meeting on August 15." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_03.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Lydia Gerard, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, holding up a new sign at their public meeting on August 15.</span></span></p>
<h2>Coming Together for Cleaner Air</h2>
<p>Taylor formed the Concerned Citizens of St. John after he and others learned that the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">US</span> Environmental Protection Agency (<span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>) determined residents in their area were at higher risk of cancer than anywhere else in the country. <a href="https://www.epa.gov/national-air-toxics-assessment/2011-national-air-toxics-assessment" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.epa.gov/national-air-toxics-assessment/2011-national-air-toxics-assessment&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1515613069646000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHs5KMOHThxOv9oMfoDZ1eptYIuZw" data-external="true">The <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>&rsquo;s latest National Air Toxics Assessment</a>, which evaluates air contaminants and estimates health risks, revealed that residents in six parish census tracts closest to the Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace have a lifetime risk of cancer from air pollution 800 times higher than the national average.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_04.jpg" alt="Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace, Louisiana." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace, Louisiana." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_04.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace, Louisiana.</span></span></p>
<p>Denka&rsquo;s LaPlace factory, formerly owned by DuPont, emits chloroprene and 28 other chemicals used to make the synthetic rubber commonly known as Neoprene. In 2010 the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> reclassified chloroprene as a likely human carcinogen, but this fact only came to the community&rsquo;s attention at the end of 2016. </p>
<p>The Concerned Citizens of St. John group holds bi-weekly public meetings at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in the town of Reserve. At meetings throughout 2017, Wilma Subra, a technical advisor to the environmental advocacy group Louisiana Environmental Action Network (<span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">LEAN</span>), reviewed the results of <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> air monitoring from six sites in the parish, which she will continue this year.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_05.jpg" alt="Wilma Subra, LEAN&rsquo;s technical advisor, at a meeting of the Concerned Citizens of St. John the Baptist Parish in Reserve, Louisiana, on June 27, 2017." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Wilma Subra, LEAN&rsquo;s technical advisor, at a meeting of the Concerned Citizens of St. John the Baptist Parish in Reserve, Louisiana, on June 27, 2017." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_05.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Wilma Subra, LEAN&rsquo;s technical advisor, at a meeting of the Concerned Citizens of St. John the Baptist Parish in Reserve, Louisiana, on June 27, 2017.</span></span></p>
<p>After the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>&rsquo;s concerns became public, Denka agreed to cut harmful emissions by up to 85 percent. Yet a year after air monitoring began, pollution levels were actually worse at five of the six sites. And that was despite the plant making costly improvements due to an agreement with regulators, <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/20/health/louisiana-toxic-town/index.html" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/20/health/louisiana-toxic-town/index.html&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1515613069646000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHWEoX4wIe7TLKSBOjwFkzwG0TlzA" data-external="true">according to <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">CNN</span>.</a> On December 19, at the group&rsquo;s last meeting of 2017, Subra went over the latest <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> data: Chloroprene emissions are, at times, still well above <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>-recommended standards.</p>
<p>As I documented Concerned Citizens throughout 2017 for DeSmog, I watched it grow into an advocacy force to be reckoned with &mdash; a unity and power they acknowledged at a Christmas celebration following their last meeting.</p>
<p><span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-dquo">&ldquo;</span>The group had some growing pains over the course of the year, but we are now stronger than ever,&rdquo; Taylor told me. &ldquo;Our group can&rsquo;t be influenced by anyone, which makes us dangerous.&rdquo;</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_06.jpg" alt="Pastor Lionel Murphy Jr. at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve. Pastor Murphy made the church available as a meeting place for the Concerned Citizens of St. John. The church has been broken in to three times since the meetings began." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Pastor Lionel Murphy Jr. at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve. Pastor Murphy made the church available as a meeting place for the Concerned Citizens of St. John. The church has been broken in to three times since the meetings began." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_06.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Pastor Lionel Murphy Jr. at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve. Pastor Murphy made the church available as a meeting place for the Concerned Citizens of St. John. The church has been broken into three times since the meetings began.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_07.jpg" alt="Robert Taylor, playing organ at a service held at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve, where the Concerned Citizens of St. John holds most of its meetings." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Robert Taylor, playing organ at a service held at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve, where the Concerned Citizens of St. John holds most of its meetings." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_07.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Robert Taylor, playing organ at a service held at the Tchoupitoulas Chapel in Reserve, where the Concerned Citizens of St. John holds most of its meetings.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_08.jpg" alt="Shondrell Perrilloux holding a sign up as she takes the podium at a parish council meeting." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Shondrell Perrilloux holding a sign up as she takes the podium at a parish council meeting." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_08.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Shondrell Perrilloux holding a sign up as she takes the podium at a parish council meeting.</span></span></p>
<h2>All Politics Is Local</h2>
<p>In 2018 Concerned Citizens plans to find and back candidates to run for local offices in order to replace the politicians who brushed off their concerns in 2017. &ldquo;Block by block, precinct by precinct, we are planning to choose candidates who will represent our interests over the industry&rsquo;s,&rdquo; Taylor said.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_09.jpg" alt="Geraldine Watkins (center), shown here at the November 29, 2017 parish council meeting, lives in LaPlace, less than a half mile from Denka's plant." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Geraldine Watkins (center), shown here at the November 29, 2017 parish council meeting, lives in LaPlace, less than a half mile from Denka's plant." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_09.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Geraldine Watkins (center), shown here at the November 29, 2017 parish council meeting, lives in LaPlace, less than a half mile from Denka&rsquo;s plant.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_10.jpg" alt="Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace is close to the 5th Ward Elementary School and residents' homes in Reserve and LaPlace, Louisiana. Flight made possible by SouthWings." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace is close to the 5th Ward Elementary School and residents' homes in Reserve and LaPlace, Louisiana. Flight made possible by SouthWings." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_10.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Denka Performance Elastomer factory in LaPlace is close to the 5th Ward Elementary School and residents&rsquo; homes in Reserve and LaPlace, Louisiana. Flight made possible by <a href="https://www.southwings.org/">SouthWings</a>.</span></span></p>
<p>Geraldine Watkins, a 76-year-old great grandmother and member of Concerned Citizens, is considering running for office herself. Protecting the children who are forced to breathe the parish&rsquo;s toxic air has become her life&rsquo;s mission. </p>
<p>She has no intention of giving up the fight for clean air until Denka adheres to the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>&rsquo;s recommended emission standard of 0.2 micrograms per cubic meter, a figure printed on the red t-shirts the group wears.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_11.jpg" alt="Members of Concerned Citizens of St. John at a parish council meeting in LaPlace, Louisiana, on March 28 wearing red t-shirts printed with Only 0.2 will do, emphasizing their point that chloroprene emissions should not exceed the EPA's recommendation." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Members of Concerned Citizens of St. John at a parish council meeting in LaPlace, Louisiana, on March 28 wearing red t-shirts printed with Only 0.2 will do, emphasizing their point that chloroprene emissions should not exceed the EPA's recommendation." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_11.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Members of Concerned Citizens of St. John at a parish council meeting in LaPlace, Louisiana, on March 28 wearing red t-shirts printed with &ldquo;Only 0.2 will do,&rdquo; emphasizing their point that chloroprene emissions should not exceed the EPA&rsquo;s recommendation.</span></span></p>
<p>The <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> emissions limits are determined with the goal of keeping the cancer risk from air pollution to less than one in every million people. When that goal is not achievable, the agency sets standards based on the &ldquo;upper limit of acceptability,&rdquo; which is a risk of 100 in a million people. That figure is the basis for the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>&rsquo;s 0.2 micrograms per cubic meter standard in St. John the Baptist Parish.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_12.jpg" alt="Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality (LDEQ) Secretary Dr. Chuck Brown before addressing the parish council on November 14." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality (LDEQ) Secretary Dr. Chuck Brown before addressing the parish council on November 14." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_12.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality (LDEQ) Secretary Dr. Chuck Brown before addressing the parish council on November 14.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_13.jpg" alt="Members of the Concerned Citizens of St. John pack the November 14 parish council meeting the night LDEQ Secretary Dr. Chuck Brown updated the council, but the group members were not given a chance to ask him questions." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Members of the Concerned Citizens of St. John pack the November 14 parish council meeting the night LDEQ Secretary Dr. Chuck Brown updated the council, but the group members were not given a chance to ask him questions." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_13.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Members of the Concerned Citizens of St. John pack the November 14 parish council meeting the night LDEQ Secretary Dr. Chuck Brown updated the council, but the group members were not given a chance to ask him questions.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_14.jpg" alt="Louisiana's state health officer Dr. Jimmy Guidry at the November 14, 2017 parish council meeting, saying there is no health emergency in the parish. At a December 2016 council meeting, however, he acknowledged that no one should have to breathe chloroprene." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Louisiana's state health officer Dr. Jimmy Guidry at the November 14, 2017 parish council meeting, saying there is no health emergency in the parish. At a December 2016 council meeting, however, he acknowledged that no one should have to breathe chloroprene." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_14.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Louisiana&rsquo;s state health officer Dr. Jimmy Guidry at the November 14, 2017, parish council meeting, saying there is no health emergency in the parish. At a December 2016 council meeting, however, he acknowledged that &ldquo;no one should have to breathe chloroprene.&rdquo;</span></span></p>
<p>Denka and Dr. Chuck Brown, the state&rsquo;s top environmental regulator, have challenged the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>&rsquo;s findings. Watkins and the other members of Concerned Citizens say they have no reason to believe the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> got it wrong. </p>
<p>Though the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> declined to comment when I asked if there were any problems with its findings on chloroprene, citing it as an open case, <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/20/health/louisiana-toxic-town/index.html" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=https://www.cnn.com/2017/10/20/health/louisiana-toxic-town/index.html&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1515613069646000&amp;usg=AFQjCNHWEoX4wIe7TLKSBOjwFkzwG0TlzA" data-external="true"><span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">CNN</span> reported</a> that an <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> spokesperson said the science behind the agency&rsquo;s findings was solid.</p>
<p><span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-dquo">&ldquo;</span>We appreciate that the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span> warned us about the chloroprene,&rdquo; Watkins told me, but it is clear to her that she and other parish residents &ldquo;are mere guinea pigs in the scheme of things. The lack of action by the government since the <span class="m_8636167004779668180gmail-caps">EPA</span>&rsquo;s findings were released makes it complicit in allowing Denka and DuPont to poison us.&rdquo;</p>
<p>In the new year, in addition to entering local politics, the Concerned Citizens of St. John also plan to form an alliance with other citizens groups in Cancer Alley which are also standing up to pollution. </p>
<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m not just fighting for myself. I&rsquo;m fighting for everyone in the parish, especially the children,&rdquo; Watkins said.</p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_15.jpg" alt="The Handys, residents of LaPlace who live across from Denka's plant. George Handy, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, purchased the house before learning about the local chloroprene emissions." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="The Handys, residents of LaPlace who live across from Denka's plant. George Handy, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, purchased the house before learning about the local chloroprene emissions." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_15.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">The Handys, residents of LaPlace who live across from Denka&rsquo;s plant. George Handy, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, purchased the house before learning about the local chloroprene emissions.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_16.jpg" alt="Councilmember Larry Sorapuru, the only councilmember in St. John the Baptist Parish who the concerned citizen group feels is standing up for them, speaking at a town hall meeting on pollution in LaPlace on November 26." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Councilmember Larry Sorapuru, the only councilmember in St. John the Baptist Parish who the concerned citizen group feels is standing up for them, speaking at a town hall meeting on pollution in LaPlace on November 26." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_16.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Councilmember Larry Sorapuru, the only councilmember in St. John the Baptist Parish who the concerned citizen group feels is standing up for them, speaking at a town hall meeting on pollution in LaPlace on November 26.</span></span></p>
<p><span class="wf_caption" style="display: block; max-width: 640px; width: 100%;"><noscript><img src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_17.jpg" alt="Mary Hampton, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, listening to the results of the latest air monitoring test at a group meeting on December 18." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;"></noscript><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%203%202'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="Mary Hampton, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, listening to the results of the latest air monitoring test at a group meeting on December 18." width="640" style="width: 100%; margin: auto;" data-src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/legacy/images/images_2018_01/2018_0109ds_17.jpg" loading="lazy"><span style="text-align: left; margin-top: 3px; display: block;">Mary Hampton, a member of the Concerned Citizens of St. John, listening to the results of the latest air monitoring test at a group meeting on December 18.</span></span></p>
